          "body": "Verses 5-8 are the chapter's most theologically dense social analysis. The premise is social misidentification: in the present corrupt order the fool (*naval*) is called noble (*nadiv*) and the rogue (*kilay*) is called generous. Isaiah is not describing error; he is describing inversion — the very categories of moral worth have been reversed. Verse 6 then unpacks what the fool actually is: his nonsense-speech is rooted in inward inclination toward wickedness and ungodliness (*choneph*), issues in theological error against the LORD, and manifests socially in withholding food from the hungry and drink from the thirsty. The connection is precise: ideological apostasy from the LORD produces social predation of the vulnerable. Verse 7 parallels this with the rogue — his 'weapons' (*keli*) are evil; he devises schemes to destroy the afflicted with slander, and he does so specifically when the needy one speaks what is right. The rogue's violence is not random but targeted at those whose just cause exposes him. Against these two, verse 8 places the *nadiv* who devises *nadiv* plans and by them stands. The noble man's defining quality is a consistency between what he plans and what he does — the structural opposite of the fool who says one thing and does another. John Calvin's commentary on this passage rightly identifies the social inversion of vv. 5-6 as a diagnostic sign of a society in which the knowledge of God has been suppressed: 'When men cease to fear God they lose the ability to name things rightly.'"
