        "excerpt": "Rise up, you women who are at ease, and hear my voice; give ear to my word, you complacent daughters.",
        "body": "Isaiah's address to the 'women who are at ease' (*shaanan*) is one of the Bible's most precise pastoral diagnoses of spiritual complacency. The address echoes and develops his earlier oracle against the daughters of Zion in Isaiah 3:16-4:1, but here the tone shifts from rebuke of vanity to alarm before imminent agricultural and civic catastrophe. The women are not accused of specific moral crimes; they are accused of *not hearing* — of treating the present comfortable order as permanent. Their sin is the sin of the age: trusting in what exists rather than attending to the prophetic word about what is coming.\n\nThe specificity of verse 10 is remarkable for prophetic literature: 'within a year and a few days.' Isaiah is not speaking in vague eschatological terms; he is naming an agricultural calendar — the coming vintage and harvest will not arrive as expected. Most commentators (Oswalt, Young, Motyer) read this as pointing to the Assyrian devastation of the Judean countryside under Sennacherib in 701 BC, which historical records and 2 Kings 18-19 confirm was catastrophic for the agricultural economy of Judah. But the chapter's deepening context — the 'until' of verse 15 and the eschatological scope of verses 16-20 — means the near fulfillment is also a type of every subsequent judgment against complacency within God's covenant people.\n\nThe mourning commands of verses 11-12 are pointed precisely because they reverse the women's current posture. They are currently clothed and at ease; they are told to strip and put on sackcloth. They are currently enjoying the fruit of pleasant fields and fruitful vines; they are told to beat their breasts for those same fields and vines because they will be lost. The list of verse 14 — palace, populated city, hill, watchtower — is a catalog of civilization's achievements reduced to caves for wild donkeys. The desolation is total: not just agricultural but civic, not just outer territories but Jerusalem's own center.\n\nThe pastoral force of this section extends to any congregation that has identified present comfort with spiritual health. Tim Keller's observation about the prophets is apt here: Isaiah is not warning the overtly wicked but the comfortable — those whose ease has made them deaf to the prophetic word. The chapter will not stay in this desolation, but it insists on sitting here long enough to be heard.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaanan* (at ease/complacent, vv.9,11) — the same root reappears positively in v.18 (*secure* dwellings). The word is not inherently negative; the negative meaning in vv.9-11 is contextual — ease built on a false foundation. *Batach* (v.9, overconfident/trusting) — the word for trust/security; used here ironically of misplaced confidence, as contrasted with *betach* (v.17) where confidence is the legitimate fruit of righteousness."
