        "body": "Verses 16-18 are the chapter's doctrinal core for social theology, and their sequence is irreversible. Justice (*mishpat*) will dwell in the wilderness (v.16) — even the previously ungoverned spaces come under covenant order. Righteousness (*tsedaqah*) will abide in the fertile field (v.16) — the productive land is no longer subject to the fool's withholding and the rogue's schemes. Then, and only then: the work of righteousness is peace (*shalom*, v.17), and the service of righteousness is quietness (*shaqat*) and confidence (*betach*) forever.\n\nThe causal sequence is Isaiah's counter-argument to every political strategy that tries to secure peace without righteousness. The nations of Judah's world — Egypt, Assyria, Babylon — offered security through alliance, tribute, and military balance. Isaiah's consistent answer (chapters 30-31) is that peace secured by bypassing righteousness is not peace but a covenant with death. The Spirit-age social order reverses the foolish inversion of 32:5-7 at the root: when the Spirit produces justice and righteousness, peace becomes the inevitable harvest. The word *avodah* (service, v.17) deepens the idea — righteousness is not a single act but a sustained orientation, a practice, a mode of life whose natural fruit is quietness.\n\nVerse 18 delivers the pastoral promise in the most domestic terms: 'my people will live in a peaceful habitation, and in secure dwellings and in undisturbed resting places.' Notice the three spatial words: *naveh* (habitation — the pastoral dwelling, the home), *mishkan* (dwelling — the tent of settled residence), *menuchah* (resting places — the Sabbath word for rest, used in Genesis 2:2-3 of God's own rest and in Psalm 95:11 of the rest promised to Israel). The Spirit-age is a Sabbath civilization — not escapist rest but the restedness of a people whose governance and relationships are properly ordered by the righteousness the Spirit has poured out.\n\nJonathan Edwards's treatment of the peace that flows from righteousness in *Religious Affections* is relevant here: Edwards consistently argued that genuine spiritual affections — produced by the Spirit, not manufactured by the flesh — manifest in social and ethical fruit. Isaiah 32:16-18 is the prophetic ground for that argument: the Spirit's work is not merely personal-experiential but structurally transforms the social order from justice at the margins to rest at the center.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsedaqah* (vv.16,17) — covenantal righteousness, right relationship with God expressed in right relationship with others. *Shalom* (vv.17,18) — integrated wholeness, the flourishing that results from properly ordered relationships. *Betach* (confidence, v.17) — the same root as the wrongly-placed confidence of *batach* in vv.9,11; here it is the rightly-placed security that results from the Spirit's work, not from present prosperity."
